<div class=Section1>

<h3 align=center style='text-align:center'>Verification of Comparison
Operations</h3>

<h3><span style='font-weight:normal;mso-bidi-font-weight:bold'>Verification of
the comparison operators has to be handled differently than the logical
operations.<span style='mso-spacerun:yes'>  </span>The result can now differ
depending on whether the operands are considered to be signed or unsigned
numbers.<span style='mso-spacerun:yes'>  </span>For both cases however, the
assertions will look identical <span class=GramE>( <b>Except</b></span> for
ALUop ):<o:p></o:p></span></h3>

<p class=MsoNormal style='mso-layout-grid-align:none;text-autospace:none'><span
style='font-family:"Courier New"'><o:p>&nbsp;</o:p></span></p>

<p class=MsoNormal style='mso-layout-grid-align:none;text-autospace:none'><span
style='font-family:"Courier New"'><span style='mso-spacerun:yes'>  
</span>--Antecedent Expression<o:p></o:p></span></p>

<p class=MsoNormal style='mso-layout-grid-align:none;text-autospace:none'><span
style='font-family:"Courier New"'><span style='mso-spacerun:yes'>  
</span>antecedent_expr &lt;= true when ALUop=&quot;1011&quot; else false;<o:p></o:p></span></p>

<p class=MsoNormal style='mso-layout-grid-align:none;text-autospace:none'><span
style='font-family:"Courier New"'><o:p>&nbsp;</o:p></span></p>

<p class=MsoNormal style='mso-layout-grid-align:none;text-autospace:none'><span
style='font-family:"Courier New"'><span style='mso-spacerun:yes'>  
</span>--Consequent Expression<o:p></o:p></span></p>

<p class=MsoNormal style='mso-layout-grid-align:none;text-autospace:none'><span
style='font-family:"Courier New"'><span style='mso-spacerun:yes'>   </span><span
class=SpellE>consequent_expr</span> &lt;= true when <span class=GramE>( (</span>
A &lt; B) AND<span style='mso-spacerun:yes'>  </span>(R =
X&quot;0000_0000_0000_0001&quot; )) OR ( ( A &gt;= B) AND(R= <o:p></o:p></span></p>

<p class=MsoNormal style='mso-layout-grid-align:none;text-autospace:none'><span
style='font-family:"Courier New"'><span
style='mso-spacerun:yes'>                      </span>X&quot;0000_0000_0000_0000&quot;
)) else false;<span style='mso-spacerun:yes'>    </span><o:p></o:p></span></p>

<p class=MsoNormal style='mso-layout-grid-align:none;text-autospace:none'><span
style='font-family:"Courier New"'><span style='mso-spacerun:yes'>       </span><o:p></o:p></span></p>

<h3><span style='font-weight:normal;mso-bidi-font-weight:bold'>So how do we differentiate
between signed and unsigned operands in our design?<span
style='mso-spacerun:yes'>  </span>The VHDL operations ‘&lt;’ and ‘&gt;=’ for <span
class=SpellE>std_logic_vectors</span> are defined inside of the IEEE library
and we can choose which definition to use.<span style='mso-spacerun:yes'> 
</span>The first step in doing so is to split up the signed and unsigned
operations into two separate entities as shown in Figure 7.<span
style='mso-spacerun:yes'>  </span>This has to be done because it is not
possible to have two definitions for the same operator, ‘&lt; signed’ and ‘&lt;
unsigned’, defined within the same scope.<o:p></o:p></span></h3>

<h3><span style='font-weight:normal;mso-bidi-font-weight:bold'><o:p>&nbsp;</o:p></span></h3>

<h3 align=center style='text-align:center'><!--[if gte vml 1]><v:shapetype
 id="_x0000_t75" coordsize="21600,21600" o:spt="75" o:preferrelative="t"
 path="m@4@5l@4@11@9@11@9@5xe" filled="f" stroked="f">
 <v:stroke joinstyle="miter"/>
 <v:formulas>
  <v:f eqn="if lineDrawn pixelLineWidth 0"/>
  <v:f eqn="sum @0 1 0"/>
